This paper is about accelerating the inference procedure of deep convolutional neural networks through a pruning method. The paper focuses on image classification benchmarks, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a new pruning algorithm, which involves training, pruning, and retraining stages, indicating that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also discusses the optimization space and information loss, which are relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and neural networks (cs.NE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves experiments and performance evaluation, which suggests that it could also belong to the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category.
